{{For|the method or style of [[handwriting]] that combines [[cursive]] and non-cursive letters within a single word|print writing}}
'''Writeprint''' is a method in [[forensic linguistics]] of establishing author identification over the internet, likened to a digital fingerprint. Identity is established through a comparison of distinguishing [[stylometry|stylometric]] characteristics of an unknown written text with known samples of the suspected author ([[writer invariant]]s). Even without a suspect, writeprint provides potential background characteristics of the author, such as nationality and education.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Li|first1=Jiexun|last2=Zheng|first2=Rong|last3=Chen|first3=Hsinchun|title=From Fingerprint to Writeprint|journal=Communications of the ACM|date=April 2006|volume=49|issue=4|pages=76–82|doi=10.1145/1121949.1121951|url=https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1121951}}</ref>
There are five broad aspects to author identification in writeprint: :*lexical features- The analysis of the [[lexicon]], the author's choice of vocabulary. :*syntactic features- The analysis of the author's writing style and sentence structure, such as: punctuation, use of passive voice, and sentence complexity. :*structural features- The analysis of the author's organization of the work. These include paragraph length, spacing, and indentation. :*content-specific features- The analysis of the language that is contextually significant to subject of the written work. Examples include the use of slang or acronyms that are specific to a crime like pirating software or hacking. :*idiosyncratic features- The analysis of errors and other ungrammatical elements that may be unique to the author.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Abbasi|first1=Ahmed|last2=Chen|first2=Hsinchun|last3=Nunamaker Jr.|first3=Jay F.|title=Stylometric Identification in Electronic Markets: Scalability and Robustness|journal=Journal of Management Information System|date=Summer 2008|volume=25|issue=1|pages=49–78|jstor=40398926}}</ref>
While the five features above are the traditional methods of author identification, there are features unique to online text. Features such as choice in font, the use of emojis, and links to other websites all provide a path to identification which is absent in traditional text analysis.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rehmeyer|first1=Juli|title=Digital Fingerprints|journal=Science News|date=Jan 13, 2007|volume=171|issue=2|pages=26–28|jstor=3982506}}</ref>
